 Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Sully","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armelle, Christophe, Geralde, Luce, Pierre, Reynald.","English: of Norman origin, a habitational name from any of the three places called Sully in Calvados (Normandy), Aisne (Picardy), and Loiret (Centre); see 6 below.","English: of Norman origin, perhaps a habitational name from Sully (Glamorgan). However, the placename is manorial in origin, from the Norman surname in 1 above, which is recorded in Glamorgan in the 12th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Soley","meanings":["English: variant of   Sully  .","Catalan: variant of <b>Solell</b>, a topographic name from <i>solell</i> ‘sunny side, southern slope’, from a derivative of <i>sol</i> ‘sun’. Compare   Sol   2."]},{"name":"Solley","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Sully  ."]},{"name":"Solly","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Sully  .","Irish: variant of   Salley  ."]}]},{"name":"Guillaume","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>William</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Guillaume de Sully I was born in 1342, in Berry, Cher, Centre, France, his father, Guyon De Sully, was 32 and his mother, Marie De Chauvigny, was 32. He married Isabeau De Maligny in 1375, in France. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 3 daughters. He died on 28 May 1381, at the age of 39."},"et":{"1342–28 MAY 1381":"1342–28. mai 1381","1330–1391":"1330–1391","1342–1381":"1342–1381","1344–Male":"1344–Surnud","1355–Female":"1355–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1375–Male":"1375–Surnud","1375–Female":"1375–Surnud","1380–Female":"1380–Surnud","1390–Female":"1390–Surnud","1310–1354":"1310–1354","1310–Female":"1310–Surnud","28 MAY 1381":"28. mai 1381","1330":"1330","1381":"1381","1380":"1380","1391":"1391","1390":"1390","       1354":"1354","1355":"1355","1344":"1344","Abt 1375":"umbes 1375","1354":"1354","1310":"1310","1342":"1342","1375":"1375","France":"Prantsusmaa","Berry,Châtillon-sur-Cher, Centre-Val de Loire, France":"Berry, Cher, Centre, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1342–28 MAY 1381":"1342–28. toukokuuta 1381","1330–1391":"1330–1391","1342–1381":"1342–1381","1344–Male":"1344–Kuollut","1355–Female":"1355–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1375–Male":"1375–Kuollut","1375–Female":"1375–Kuollut","1380–Female":"1380–Kuollut","1390–Female":"1390–Kuollut","1310–1354":"1310–1354","1310–Female":"1310–Kuollut","28 MAY 1381":"28. toukokuuta 1381","1330":"1330","1381":"1381","1380":"1380","1391":"1391","1390":"1390","       1354":"1354","1355":"1355","1344":"1344","Abt 1375":"noin 1375","1354":"1354","1310":"1310","1342":"1342","1375":"1375","France":"Ranska","Berry,Châtillon-sur-Cher, Centre-Val de Loire, France":"Berry, C